3","1285":"1285","1230":"1230","1284":"1284","about 1253":"omkring 1253","1282":"1282","Long Itchington, Warwickshire, England":"Long Itchington, Warwickshire, England","Rotherfield Greys, Oxfordshire, England":"Rotherfield Greys, Oxfordshire, England","Rotherfield Greys, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Rotherfield Greys, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"about 1253–1285":"circa 1253–1285","1253–1285":"1253–1285","1254–1282":"1254–1282","1231–1285":"1231–1285","1285–1347":"1285–1347","1235–Male":"1235–Overleden","1230–Female":"1230–Overleden","1259":"1259","1347":"1347","1235":"1235","1254":"1254","1231":"1231","1253":"1253","1285":"1285","1230":"1230","1284":"1284","about 1253":"circa 1253","1282":"1282","Long Itchington, Warwickshire, England":"Long Itchington, Warwickshire, England","Rotherfield Greys, Oxfordshire, England":"Rotherfield Greys, Oxfordshire, England","Rotherfield Greys, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Rotherfield Greys, Oxfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1253–1285":"about 1253–1285","1253–1285":"1253–1285","1254–1282":"1254–1282","1231–1285":"1231–1285","1285–1347":"1285–1347","1235–Male":"1235–Deceased","1230–Female":"1230–Deceased","1259":"1259","1347":"1347","1235":"1235","1254":"1254","1231":"1231","1253":"1253","1285":"1285","1230":"1230","1284":"1284","about 1253":"about 1253","1282":"1282","Long Itchington, Warwickshire, England":"Long Itchington, Warwickshire, England","Rotherfield Greys, Oxfordshire, England":"Rotherfield Greys, Oxfordshire, England","Rotherfield Greys, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Rotherfield Greys, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Bretton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin) and French: variant of   Breton  .","English: habitational name from any of the places called from Bretton in Derbyshire and Yorkshire, both of which mean ‘settlement of the Britons’, from Old English <i>Brettas</i> ‘Briton’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’."],"variants":[{"name":"Breton","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Marcel, Andre, Normand, Renald, Adelard, Alphonse, Armand, Gaetan, Laurent, Serge, Adrien, Aime.","French, Breton (mainly Finistère), and English (of Norman origin): ethnic name for a Breton, from Old French <i>breton</i>, oblique case of <i>bret</i> (see   Bret  ). Compare   Lebreton  , see also English   Brett  .","History: In North America, this surname was originally also a secondary surname or <i>dit</i> (‘also called’) name, borne by Jean Élie/Hélie <i>dit</i> (Le) Breton from Ménéac in Morbihan, Brittany (France), who married Jeanne Labbé in Sainte-Famille, Île d'Orléans, QC, in 1669. His descendants also bear the surname   Elie  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":6,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Bretton was born about 1253, in Long Itchington, Warwickshire, England, his father, Nicholas De Bretton, was 19 and his mother, Mrs. Nicholas Breton, was 24. He married Avicia de Chetwode in 1284, in Rotherfield Greys, Oxfordshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1285, in Rotherfield Greys, Oxfordshire, England, at the age of 33."},"et":{"about 1253–1285":"umbes 1253–1285","1253–1285":"1253–1285","1254–1282":"1254–1282","1231–1285":"1231–1285","1285–1347":"1285–1347","1235–Male":"1235–Surnud","1230–Female":"1230–Surnud","1259":"1259","1347":"1347","1235":"1235","1254":"1254","1231":"1231","1253":"1253","1285":"1285","1230":"1230","1284":"1284","about 1253":"umbes 1253","1282":"1282","Long Itchington, Warwickshire, England":"Long Itchington, Warwickshire, England","Rotherfield Greys, Oxfordshire, England":"Rotherfield Greys, Oxfordshire, England","Rotherfield Greys, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Rotherfield Greys, Oxfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1253–1285":"noin 1253–1285","1253–1285":"1253–1285","1254–1282":"1254–1282","1231–1285":"1231–1285","1285–1347":"1285–1347","1235–Male":"1235–Kuollut","1230–Female":"1230–Kuollut","1259":"1259","1347":"1347","1235":"1235","1254":"1254","1231":"1231","1253":